<subSubSection id="56664E2DB5AAEC95CDAE373CCD3444D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="notes">
<paragraph id="A374D02658E8F48DDD2B5DD581870C8D" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB4C1D22CB4AC92AF2627C0A5AA31D55" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName id="72E126EBBCD932D585140FB5E5603A1F" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ceratostomataceae" genus="Microthecium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Microthecium masonii" order="Melanosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="masonii">Microthecium masonii</taxonomicName>
is characterized by ostiolate ascomata and ellipsoidal to fusiform, faintly striate-reticulate ascospores. The same type of ascospore ornamentation is also observed in 
<taxonomicName id="85FA6985CAC1BD448764C60E46FF4044" genus="Mi." lsidName="Mi. micropertusum" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="micropertusum">Mi. micropertusum</taxonomicName>
, but this latter species is easily distinguished by the presence of inconspicuous ridges forming a very coarse reticulum and a phialidic asexual morph.
</paragraph>
